Krigging Example with Meuse data

First load the libraries

most of this is from https://rpubs.com/nabilabd/118172 and modified for looking at lead and them demonstrating how to create a grid for krigging

library(sp)
library(gstat)
# packages for manipulation & visualization
suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(dplyr) 
  library(ggplot2)
  library(scales) 
  library(magrittr)
})
library(maps)
options(scipen = 999)  #because scientific notation is not readable by normal people :)
data(meuse)

Load the meuse data I already did some clean up.

Lead

meuse %>% as.data.frame %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x, y)) + geom_point(aes(size=lead), color="blue", alpha=3/4) + 
  ggtitle("Lead Concentration (ppm)") + coord_equal() + theme_bw()

Convert the data frame to SP type by adding the x, y or long, lat

coordinates(meuse) <- ~ x + y

Create the variogram

lzn.vgm <- variogram(log(lead)~1, meuse) # calculates sample variogram values 
lzn.fit <- fit.variogram(lzn.vgm, model=vgm(1, "Sph", 900, 1)) # fit model
plot(lzn.vgm, lzn.fit) # plot the sample values, along with the fit model

plot the observatiosn for the Muese data then plot the grided data. In this case the meuse grid already exists so we will use that to interpolate.

# load spatial domain to interpolate over
data("meuse.grid")
# to compare, recall the bubble plot above; those points were what there were values for. this is much more sparse
plot1 <- meuse %>% as.data.frame %>%
  ggplot(aes(x, y)) + geom_point(size=1) + coord_equal() + 
  ggtitle("Points with measurements")
# this is clearly gridded over the region of interest
plot2 <- meuse.grid %>% as.data.frame %>%
  ggplot(aes(x, y)) + geom_point(size=1) + coord_equal() + 
  ggtitle("Points at which to estimate")
library(gridExtra)
grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol = 2)

Run the krigging

coordinates(meuse.grid) <- ~ x + y # step 3 above
lzn.kriged <- krige(log(lead) ~ 1, meuse, meuse.grid, model=lzn.fit)
[using ordinary kriging]

plot the krigging with meuse grid

lzn.kriged %>% as.data.frame %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y)) + geom_tile(aes(fill=var1.pred)) + coord_equal() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "yellow", high="red") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels=comma) + scale_y_continuous(labels=comma) +
  theme_bw()

Now lets create a grid on our own. in the case we will create a grid of 250 map units.

data(meuse)
coordinates(meuse) <- ~ x + y
#define the gride size 
grd <- as.data.frame(spsample(meuse, "regular", n=250))
#convert the varriables for location so they are named x, y
names(grd) <- c("x", "y")
coordinates(grd) <- c("x", "y")
#convert to a grid
gridded(grd) <- TRUE  # Create SpatialPixel object
fullgrid(grd) <- TRUE  # Create SpatialGrid object
plot(grd) # plot the new grid

now run krigging on our new grid

lzn.kriged <- krige(log(lead) ~ 1, meuse, grd, model=lzn.fit)
[using ordinary kriging]
lzn.kriged %>% as.data.frame %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y)) + geom_tile(aes(fill=var1.pred)) + coord_equal() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "yellow", high="red") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels=comma) + scale_y_continuous(labels=comma) +
  theme_bw()

another example with a higher resolution to demonstrate

data(meuse)
coordinates(meuse) <- ~ x + y
 
grd <- as.data.frame(spsample(meuse, "regular", n=2500))
names(grd) <- c("x", "y")
coordinates(grd) <- c("x", "y")
gridded(grd) <- TRUE  # Create SpatialPixel object
fullgrid(grd) <- TRUE  # Create SpatialGrid object
plot(grd)

lzn.kriged <- krige(log(lead) ~ 1, meuse, grd, model=lzn.fit)
[using ordinary kriging]
lzn.kriged %>% as.data.frame %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=x, y=y)) + geom_tile(aes(fill=var1.pred)) + coord_equal() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "yellow", high="red") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels=comma) + scale_y_continuous(labels=comma) +
  theme_bw()
